00:54:57.078 --> 00:54:58.907
I thought that would really help.

00:54:58.907 --> 00:55:01.861
I did end up cussing like a sailor

00:55:01.861 --> 00:55:05.861
and we ended up back to
our love for each other.

00:55:07.105 --> 00:55:10.352
The one place we came
together was where you said

00:55:10.352 --> 00:55:13.970
about taking money out of politics.

00:55:13.970 --> 00:55:18.137
So my question for you has
been I would love to hear

00:55:19.123 --> 00:55:22.173
how you got over your own reactivity

00:55:22.173 --> 00:55:25.340
which I imagine you have in listening.

00:55:27.174 --> 00:55:29.674
So I'd find that very helpful.

00:55:32.621 --> 00:55:36.199
- Well (laughs).

00:55:36.199 --> 00:55:39.944
- [Woman] Reveal your
trade secrets please.

00:55:39.944 --> 00:55:44.413
- You know I've written
about emotional labor

00:55:44.413 --> 00:55:48.072
and this kind of research
I think requires it.

00:55:48.072 --> 00:55:50.572
But actually it's interesting.

00:55:52.381 --> 00:55:55.799
The job of listening was
to take my own political

00:55:55.799 --> 00:55:59.799
and moral alarm system
off while I was listening

00:56:00.645 --> 00:56:04.097
so that the purpose of my
being there was to learn.

00:56:04.097 --> 00:56:05.681
I'll give you an example
of how that worked.

00:56:05.681 --> 00:56:09.014
There was an evangelical minister's wife

00:56:11.900 --> 00:56:14.823
who said at a meeting of Republican women

00:56:14.823 --> 00:56:18.490
of southwest Louisiana
I love Rush Limbaugh.

00:56:19.981 --> 00:56:23.064
You know the conservative radio host.

00:56:24.938 --> 00:56:28.476
And I had a gag response to that at first

00:56:28.476 --> 00:56:30.914
and then a thought, ooh
I'd really like to talk

00:56:30.914 --> 00:56:32.414
to you about that.

00:56:34.535 --> 00:56:38.702
And we went out for sweet
teas, what you do there,

00:56:41.776 --> 00:56:44.175
and she said I love Rush Limbaugh

00:56:44.175 --> 00:56:46.425
because he hates feminazis.

00:56:47.352 --> 00:56:51.104
I thought I hope they haven't Googled me.

00:56:51.104 --> 00:56:52.187
Second Shift.

00:56:56.600 --> 00:56:59.733
And then environmental wackos and so on.

00:56:59.733 --> 00:57:01.441
She went on and then she
was looking at my face

00:57:01.441 --> 00:57:05.378
which I was trying to hold
neutrally and she said

00:57:05.378 --> 00:57:06.961
is it hard for you?

00:57:07.939 --> 00:57:09.651
I know you don't agree with me.

00:57:09.651 --> 00:57:13.715
Cause I told her exactly who
I was and what I believed

00:57:13.715 --> 00:57:18.563
or side I was on and I said
actually no, it's not hard.

00:57:18.563 --> 00:57:20.269
That's not why I'm here.

00:57:20.269 --> 00:57:21.691
I know about me.

00:57:21.691 --> 00:57:23.521
But I don't know about
you and you're doing me

00:57:23.521 --> 00:57:26.604
more of a favor than you know to open

00:57:28.108 --> 00:57:30.754
your experiences to me
and I can't tell you

00:57:30.754 --> 00:57:32.424
how I appreciate it.

00:57:32.424 --> 00:57:34.496
You know what she said then?

00:57:34.496 --> 00:57:36.164
Oh take your alarm system off.

00:57:36.164 --> 00:57:37.911
I do that too.

00:57:37.911 --> 00:57:39.621
I do it with my parishioners.

00:57:39.621 --> 00:57:41.777
I do it with my kids.

00:57:41.777 --> 00:57:44.508
And then we had that in common

00:57:44.508 --> 00:57:48.675
and could kinda move from
there across vast differences.

00:57:49.713 --> 00:57:51.180
She was the one who described heaven

00:57:51.180 --> 00:57:53.335
as a cube of gold, you know?

00:57:53.335 --> 00:57:55.335
So differences but yeah.

00:57:57.099 --> 00:58:00.889
- Well what I get out of that
is the focus on understanding

00:58:00.889 --> 00:58:04.309
as opposed to correcting or changing.

00:58:04.309 --> 00:58:05.142
- Yes.

00:58:06.300 --> 00:58:09.383
And you do wonderful work by the way.

00:58:10.529 --> 00:58:12.072
- Thank you.

00:58:12.072 --> 00:58:13.414
That was largely my question.

00:58:13.414 --> 00:58:16.744
But I guess I also wanna
ask what else did you learn

00:58:16.744 --> 00:58:19.221
about yourself in the process and ways

00:58:19.221 --> 00:58:22.060
that you had to show up differently

00:58:22.060 --> 00:58:25.186
or assumptions that you
had to check in the process

00:58:25.186 --> 00:58:27.853
of hearing others' perspectives?

00:58:29.906 --> 00:58:31.573
- Well people ask me

00:58:35.878 --> 00:58:38.795
did it change my political beliefs?

00:58:39.985 --> 00:58:42.068
And no, it didn't at all.

00:58:43.078 --> 00:58:44.787
But did it change me?

00:58:44.787 --> 00:58:45.765
Yes.

00:58:45.765 --> 00:58:49.432
I would say it did
because now I walk around

00:58:51.453 --> 00:58:53.453
with thinking how X or Y

00:58:55.068 --> 00:58:57.028
you know Janice Serino or Mike Chef

00:58:57.028 --> 00:58:59.445
would think about X or Y or Z

00:59:00.368 --> 00:59:03.174
and sometimes it makes me sad to think

00:59:03.174 --> 00:59:07.341
how they would see some things
here at our beloved Berkeley.

00:59:11.267 --> 00:59:14.017
The Antifa violence, for example,

00:59:18.320 --> 00:59:21.857
and their conclusion with that is whoa

00:59:21.857 --> 00:59:24.132
your students they think
they're the students

00:59:24.132 --> 00:59:26.965
or the fascists, you know, anyway.

00:59:28.481 --> 00:59:31.398
So it made me more worried about us

00:59:33.279 --> 00:59:36.196
and I see a kind of a defensiveness

00:59:37.147 --> 00:59:39.564
and a non-openness on my side

00:59:44.030 --> 00:59:48.197
that has me concerned and
has me wanting to work on it

00:59:49.679 --> 00:59:52.480
and I'll tell you one thing.

00:59:52.480 --> 00:59:56.647
Just two days ago I was
at the New Yorker festival

00:59:57.928 --> 01:00:02.095
and got to speak with and hear
the Reverend William Barber

01:00:04.585 --> 01:00:08.892
the Second the Moral Mondays
guy from South Carolina.

01:00:08.892 --> 01:00:12.225
Very spellbinding and very incorporative

01:00:17.631 --> 01:00:19.542
and he is really an heir I think

01:00:19.542 --> 01:00:22.709
to Martin Luther King and his openness

01:00:25.849 --> 01:00:30.789
and what he gets up and says
is I'm black, I'm white,

01:00:30.789 --> 01:00:34.453
I'm Indian, I'm some ways conservative,

01:00:34.453 --> 01:00:36.286
some ways progressive.

01:00:36.286 --> 01:00:40.203
I'm all of these things
and I want to organize,

01:00:41.651 --> 01:00:44.151
we are organizing in 30 cities

01:00:45.996 --> 01:00:50.163
a big demonstration for poor
children across the country.

01:00:52.301 --> 01:00:55.108
Hold the moral high ground.

01:00:55.108 --> 01:00:57.223
The end of his speech it
was like a congregation.

01:00:57.223 --> 01:01:00.231
A spellbinder thing and at the end of it

01:01:00.231 --> 01:01:03.735
he had each person in the audience

01:01:03.735 --> 01:01:08.568
turn to your neighbor and
say I will not be depressed.

01:01:08.568 --> 01:01:10.568
I will not be depressed.

01:01:11.542 --> 01:01:14.139
And then turn to them and
say I will get active.

01:01:14.139 --> 01:01:15.639
I will get active.

01:01:16.660 --> 01:01:18.448
And so I came home and
I thought you know what

01:01:18.448 --> 01:01:22.069
I'm gonna write Carol Christ and see

01:01:22.069 --> 01:01:24.986
if we can get this guy to Berkeley.

01:01:26.788 --> 01:01:30.371
Incorporative, we need
to be incorporative.

01:01:36.746 --> 01:01:38.829
- Hi, I am a young woman.

01:01:43.581 --> 01:01:46.543
I'm a freshman at UC Berkeley undergrad.

01:01:46.543 --> 01:01:48.904
I have grown up a military kid.

01:01:48.904 --> 01:01:51.585
I've experienced all different places

01:01:51.585 --> 01:01:54.335
and all different kinds of people

01:01:55.650 --> 01:01:57.686
and as a young woman who's going to spend

01:01:57.686 --> 01:02:02.157
the four years of Trump's
presidency at UC Berkeley

01:02:02.157 --> 01:02:04.685
how do you suggest we go about

01:02:04.685 --> 01:02:08.852
receiving our education and
going out into the world

01:02:10.009 --> 01:02:12.611
finding a job in this kind of culture

01:02:12.611 --> 01:02:14.763
that's been created and
this kind of like attitude

01:02:14.763 --> 01:02:16.802
that's been created in this country?

01:02:16.802 --> 01:02:19.398
How do you suggest we go about that?

01:02:19.398 --> 01:02:22.398
- Well classroom education, dive in.

01:02:24.148 --> 01:02:27.731
And as for your experience
here at Berkeley

01:02:30.002 --> 01:02:33.335
take yourself as a builder of a culture,

01:02:34.563 --> 01:02:37.480
of political discussion and debate.

01:02:39.605 --> 01:02:43.772
At the moment I feel that
the Berkeley campus culture

01:02:45.623 --> 01:02:49.119
of political debate reflects
the national culture.

01:02:49.119 --> 01:02:53.510
You have a few polarizing
speakers that come in

01:02:53.510 --> 01:02:55.666
in attack-defend mode.

01:02:55.666 --> 01:02:57.785
You're either for them
or you're against them.

01:02:57.785 --> 01:02:59.046
There is no middle ground.

01:02:59.046 --> 01:03:00.511
It's kind of frozen.

01:03:00.511 --> 01:03:02.506
You don't dare say what you really think.

01:03:02.506 --> 01:03:04.302
That's a problem.

01:03:04.302 --> 01:03:07.263
I think we need to really thicken up

01:03:07.263 --> 01:03:09.988
and enrich the culture.

01:03:09.988 --> 01:03:12.063
I think we need to bring theater into it.

01:03:12.063 --> 01:03:13.563
We need satirists.

01:03:15.154 --> 01:03:17.154
We need Reverend Barber.

01:03:20.441 --> 01:03:23.524
People who have all kinds of projects

01:03:25.728 --> 01:03:28.978
and I think there is an important place

01:03:31.177 --> 01:03:32.924
for Berkeley Bridge.

01:03:32.924 --> 01:03:37.091
So I would invite you to plunge
into that set of activities.

01:03:41.813 --> 01:03:43.146
- Hi, thank you.

01:03:46.041 --> 01:03:50.675
It seems pretty clear to me
that the kind of awareness

01:03:50.675 --> 01:03:54.842
that you've demonstrated about
the deep story and climate

01:03:55.788 --> 01:03:59.538
in Lake Charles has
definitely been perceived

01:04:01.037 --> 01:04:04.954
and is in many ways used
by political campaigns

01:04:07.168 --> 01:04:10.251
and news media to exacerbate the sets

01:04:14.488 --> 01:04:19.209
of being hardly done by
and others getting ahead

01:04:19.209 --> 01:04:23.376
so I guess my question is
when you were in Lake Charles

01:04:24.782 --> 01:04:28.841
what is your sense of
people's ability to recognize

01:04:28.841 --> 01:04:33.008
when they're being manipulated
and or any optimistic views

01:04:37.992 --> 01:04:41.167
of how in Lake Charles the partisan divide

01:04:41.167 --> 01:04:44.667
can be minimized or at least not inflamed?

01:04:47.186 --> 01:04:49.138
- Well there are people there,

01:04:49.138 --> 01:04:53.685
first of all, there are pockets
of progressives, of course,

01:04:53.685 --> 01:04:57.504
in this conservative country and landscape

01:04:57.504 --> 01:05:01.577
and they all have friends and relatives

01:05:01.577 --> 01:05:03.768
who don't agree with them.

01:05:03.768 --> 01:05:05.191
So actually they've gotten pretty good

01:05:05.191 --> 01:05:07.941
at how to do this bridging thing.

01:05:08.853 --> 01:05:10.886
Many of them just avoid differences

01:05:10.886 --> 01:05:13.719
and keep their bonds without that.

01:05:19.950 --> 01:05:23.950
They were as worried about
this divide as I was.

01:05:25.113 --> 01:05:29.910
That was kind of the first
thing they would say.

01:05:29.910 --> 01:05:31.946
I sort of came in like Mary Poppins.

01:05:31.946 --> 01:05:36.509
Hi, I'm Arlie Hochschild,
sociologist at Berkeley

01:05:36.509 --> 01:05:40.497
and you'll never remember my last name.

01:05:40.497 --> 01:05:43.020
So jokes and then I would say I'm worried

01:05:43.020 --> 01:05:45.103
about this growing divide

01:05:46.396 --> 01:05:47.817
and that's the first thing they would say.

01:05:47.817 --> 01:05:48.734
We are too.

01:05:49.734 --> 01:05:52.460
We're feeling cut off and we don't feel

01:05:52.460 --> 01:05:54.167
you understand us.

01:05:54.167 --> 01:05:58.334
We feel you liberal coastal
people are looking down on us.

01:06:01.936 --> 01:06:05.603
So you go write a book
and set 'em straight.

01:06:06.939 --> 01:06:08.606
What they would say.

01:06:09.823 --> 01:06:13.906
But you know what ultimately
I would love to see?

01:06:14.908 --> 01:06:18.991
I think we need new
mechanisms, social mechanisms

01:06:21.386 --> 01:06:24.553
for mixing up the American population.

01:06:25.977 --> 01:06:28.660
We know that the 46%
of Americans who voted

01:06:28.660 --> 01:06:32.327
for Donald Trump are
regionally distributed.

01:06:34.836 --> 01:06:37.433
It's the south and it's the Midwest.

01:06:37.433 --> 01:06:39.507
We know it's racially distributed.

01:06:39.507 --> 01:06:42.340
More white, fewer people of color.

01:06:44.710 --> 01:06:46.543
And class distributed.

01:06:46.543 --> 01:06:49.515
Less likely to be highly educated whites

01:06:49.515 --> 01:06:52.525
that are Democrats but much more likely

01:06:52.525 --> 01:06:56.316
if they're high school educated or lower.

01:06:56.316 --> 01:06:59.733
So given that kind of sociological divide

01:07:02.644 --> 01:07:05.727
I think we need to look to mechanisms

01:07:06.620 --> 01:07:09.672
that bridge those structural divides.

01:07:09.672 --> 01:07:13.505
We used to have before
1973 a compulsory draft

01:07:14.796 --> 01:07:16.629
which did that for men

01:07:17.686 --> 01:07:21.877
and we used to have in its
heyday through the labor movement

01:07:21.877 --> 01:07:24.969
labor unions used to do that for workers.

01:07:24.969 --> 01:07:27.733
But we don't have either
of those mechanisms today

01:07:27.733 --> 01:07:31.566
so I think it's on us
to invent new mechanisms

01:07:34.194 --> 01:07:38.277
and what I would love to
see is either a one year

01:07:42.439 --> 01:07:46.106
year of voluntary service
that kind of mixed

01:07:47.680 --> 01:07:50.680
young people up or to have a program

01:07:51.871 --> 01:07:56.061
through high schools and
to have in your junior year

01:07:56.061 --> 01:07:58.255
coastal kids go inland.

01:07:58.255 --> 01:08:00.572
Have southern kids go north.

01:08:00.572 --> 01:08:02.932
Have norther kids go
south and for three weeks

01:08:02.932 --> 01:08:05.656
be the guest in an exchange program.

01:08:05.656 --> 01:08:09.153
So you don't send your
kid off to Italy or France

01:08:09.153 --> 01:08:13.092
for their experience of the other world,

01:08:13.092 --> 01:08:15.367
your national world.

01:08:15.367 --> 01:08:19.890
What you do is introduce
them to the strangers

01:08:19.890 --> 01:08:22.390
in their own country via this.

01:08:25.136 --> 01:08:27.897
So not only I think we need two things.

01:08:27.897 --> 01:08:31.314
These new mechanisms for mixing people up

01:08:32.496 --> 01:08:36.811
and the result of that will
be to have new questioning

01:08:36.811 --> 01:08:40.016
about what are true facts and fake facts?

01:08:40.016 --> 01:08:41.808
I mean that's gonna
start some conversations

01:08:41.808 --> 01:08:43.891
that aren't going on now.

01:08:45.911 --> 01:08:48.994
So I think we need the new mechanisms

01:08:50.669 --> 01:08:52.621
and then we all need to become mediators,

01:08:52.621 --> 01:08:56.788
develop that skill set and
apply it in the new world

01:08:57.908 --> 01:08:59.657
we wanna live in.

01:08:59.657 --> 01:09:01.403
Thank you very much.

01:09:01.403 --> 01:09:04.570
(audience applauding)

01:09:07.583 --> 01:09:11.250
(upbeat instrumental music)

